{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698255/1938010101/0448.xml":{"full_text":"2\nSilver Bloc Fights\nOrder of President\nSlashing U. S. Price\nLeaders Assert Action Will Upset Money\nMarket, Create Unemployment\n\u2022(1.N.5.). President Roosevelt's proclamation cutting the\nGovernment purchase price for domestic, mined silver from\n77.57 to 64.64 cents an ounce, today presaged a fight with the\nCongressional white metal bloc.\nRelief Fight\nForecast in\nCongress\nBy WILLIAM S. NEAL\n(1.N.5.) A battle to return ad\nministration of relief to States and\ncities was forecast today as con\ntending factions prepared for open\ning of a Congressional fight over\neconomy and relief next week.\nThe movement to send relief\nback to the States, with the Fed\neral Government still aiding, is\nslated to be waged by a bi-partisan\ngroup in both Senate and House.\nThe relief issue, which was not\nexpected to be reached in Con\ngress until February or March,\nmay be forced by demands of labor\nfor repeal of the Woodrum amend\nment.\nNEW DRIVE ON\nThis provision, which committed\nthe Government to spreading the\nJ 1 ,500,000,000 WPA appropriation\nover 12 months, was designed to\nprevent agitation for a huge de\nficiency appropriation.\nBut with unemployment mount\ning. an active campaign already\nhas been opened to pave the way\nfor additional sums for the WPA\nduring the winter.\nDavid Lasser, of the Workers\nAlliance of America, which has\nadvocated huge relief appropria\ntions, issued a statement intimat\ning that officials of many cities\nare refusing to certify unemploy\nment to relief rolls in order to\nforce return of relief administra\ntion to them.\nLID TAKEN OFF\nThe PWA, he said, recently of\nfered unlimited expansion of its\nrolls in the six important indus\ntrial cities of Chicago, Detroit,.\nMilwaukee, St. Paul, Cincinnati\nand Cleveland.\n\u201cBut what happened?\u201d he\nasked. \u201cWPA reports that of the\n350,000 jobs offered, only about\n100,000 have been taken up. The\nFederal WPA officials are be\ncoming satisfied now that there\nis no great need existing in the\ncountry. Or, if there is need, the\nunemployed refuse to work.\u201d\nThe reason, Lasser said, is the\nslowness of city officials in certify\ning men and women to places on\nWPA rolls.\nSNELL PLEDGES AID\nAnticipating a declaration from\nPresident Roosevelt in his budget\nmessage to Congress in favor of\neconomy. Representative Snell of\nNew York. Republican House\nleader, pledged party aid.\n\u201cThe Republicans will sup\nport the President in any rea\nsonable economy movement,\u201d he\nsaid. \u201cWe have been fighting\nfor economy for five years.\u201d\nRepresentative Cox (D.) of\nGeorgia predicted Congress will\nwhole-heartedly back a presiden\ntial drive for economy.\n\u201cI think the disposition of\nCongress will be to go along,\u201d\n\u25a0aid Cox. \"Congress wants the\nPresident to balance the budget.\nI think that Congress will seek\nto effectuate economies wher\never possible.\u201d\nRepresentative Dies (D.) of\nTexas plans to call 100 Democrats\ntogether next week, to plan an\neconomy campaign as an aid to\nthe President\u2019s budget balancing\nprogram.\nFabtUbod Dally at 1817 H St. N. W.\nfrith Sunday Imui at th* Washington\nHerald-Time*\nEditorial and Bo*ine** Phon*\nREpubli* 1234\nfntsrsd nx the Poti Office. Waehinaton.\nD. 0., at eecond-ciaee mail mailer.\nEleanor P*tt*r\u00abon Editor and Publisher\nWfflif C. Shelton -Aisistant Publisher\nSATSB *T CARRIER IN WASHINGTON. D. C\nAND suburbs\nDaily end\nDally Sunday Bunday\nOn* Tmt 55.56 SS.IS 110.40\nSU Month* ISO I M 6.10\nThrM Month. l.\u00bb0\n0m tto\u00bb4 4t .\u00abS .>0\nte. Wb. 1\u00bb .11 M\n\u25a0ATEB BY MAIL TOR VIRGINIA, MARTLAND.\nWMT VIRGINIA AND NORTH CAROLINA\nDaily and\nDally Bunday Bunday\nOn* T*tr SC.6O S6.H 11100\nSix Month* 1........ S.M S.M TOO\nThN* Mouth* I M I.M S.M\nOn* 66 .66 I.SO\nOTHJUt ST ATES.\"' CAN ADA AND MEXICO\nDally and\nDally Sunday Sunday\nOn* T\u00abar tf.B6 ST.2O SIS 00\nSix Mon-An s ee s \u00abo f.se\nThree Month* 1.65 1.80 STB\nOn* Meath .65 -M 1.15\nAi* HAIL KrBSCRIPTiONh PATABLB\nbJ_ XM ADVANCE\nTelephone RE publie 1234\nHeaded by Senators McCarran\n(D.i u Nevada and Thomas (D.)\nof Utah, the bloc has served notice\nit will oppose the 13-cent-per-ounce\nreduction for newly nrned silver.\nRepresentatives from silver States\nalso are expected to oppose the\nproclamation.\nSEEK DISCUSSION\nDiscussions with Treasury offi\ncials, and perhaps the President,\nwere to be asked as the Western\ners complained the reduction in\nthe Government subsidy threatens\nthe mining industry, will create\nadditional unemployment and un\ni stabilize money markets.\n\u201cWe of the silver-- oducing\nStates hope a more favorable ar\nrangement can be worked out\nwith the President and Treasury\nofficials,\u201d McCarran said. \u201cThis\nreduction will bring havoc to\nthat part of the mining industry\nwhich produces silver and other\nmetals.\u201d\nSenator Thomas declared the re\nduction will cause a loss of reve\nnue to silver States through in\nability of workers \"who will be\nlaid off\u201d to pay taxes. He also\nforecast that the proclamation will\nhave other \"ill effects\u201d in the busi\nness and monetary world.\nPRICE IDENTICAL\nThe proclamation was issued by\nPresident Roosevelt at the expira\ntion of one issued on April 25,\n1935, fixing the price at 77.57\ncents an ounce. It was issued un\nder authority of an amendment to\nthe agricultural adjustment act\nwhich permits him to fix the price\nof domestic silver in excess of the\nworld and New York market price\nas a step toward stabilizing the\nindustry.\nThe new price is identical with\nthe one the President fixed on De\ncember 21, 1933. The pew price\nwill be paid by the Treasury until\nfurther notice. Friday\u2019s world price\nwas 42.92 cents an ounce.\nRussia and Japan\nSign Fishing Pact\nMOSCOW, Jan. 1 (1.N.5.).\nRelations between Soviet Russia\nand Japan, strained by the Sino-\nJapanese war, appeared to be\nsomewhat on the mend today, for\nthe time being at least, following\nconclusion of a provisional fish\neries agreement by the two powers.\nAssistant Foreign Commissar\nB. S. Stomonykov and Japanese\nAmbassador Dor Mamoru Shige\nmitsu signed a 1938 protocol cover\ning Japan\u2019s fishing rights in So\nviet Far Eastern waters.\nRep. Lea, Roosevelt\nConfer on Aviation\n(1.N.5.) Representative Lea, of\nCalifornia, chairman of the House\nInterstate and Foreign Commerce'\nCommittee, conferred with Presi-'\ndent Roosevelt late yesterday. He!\nsaid he talked concerning the two'\nbills now before his committee.\nthat would put aviation control'\nunder a single bureau or the ICC.\n\u2018Old Glory\u2019 Protects American Lives\n5\nW. M.< i|a\ni 'n\n11 lb\nto? wNBMHBIMi'\n4EBKSmmMMIIB\n-T*\" I\nTO PREVENT another disaster like\nthat of the U. S. S. Panay, American ships\nin the Chinese war zone have painted\nreplicas of \u201cOld Glory\u201d on their sides and\nPROBES START\nON 2 REPORTERS\nSLAIN IN SPAIN\nThird Scribe Reported\nWounded at Teruel\nHENDAYE. France, Jan. I.\u2014\n(I.N.S.)\u2014 British and American\nauthorities today investigated the\ndeaths of two correspondents and\nthe wounding of a third while they\nwere touring the Spanish battle\narea near Teruel.\nThose killed, according to Brit\nish advices here, were Bradish\nJohnson. Jr., 23, a member of a so\ncially prominent New York fam\nily and Paris correspondent for\nthe American magazine Spur,\nand E. R. Sheepshanks, a Briton,\ncorrespondent for Reuters news\nagency.\nThe wounded man was report\ned to be Edward J. Neil. Associated\nPress correspondent, who was said\nto have been severely wounded in\nthe left leg.\nInsurgent Spanish officials in\nformed the British charge\nd\u2019affaires, G. H. Thompson, of the\ntragedy shortly after it occurred.\nHe was told a shell hit the auto\nmobile in which the three men\nwere touring the front.\nJohnson Called\n\u201cBrilliant Writer\u201d\nNEW YORK, Jan. 1 (1.N.5.).\nBradish Johnson, 23, reported\nkilled near the Spanish civil war\nbattlefront, was described today as\na \"brilliant writer\u201d of adventure\nsome turn of mind by Robert Ren\nfro. editor of the magazine The\nSpur.\nJohnson had been Paris corre\nspondent of the magazine since\nOctober, 1936, and author of a\nmonthly column on politics and\nnight life. Renfro said.\nAlso on the staff of the Paris\nHerald, the writer reported to Ren\nfro about six weeks ago that he\nwas resigning his newspaper post\nto devote full time to the maga\nzine assignment.\nJohnson, a Harvard student\nfrom 1930 to 1933, left college to\nseek adventure, chose first a career\nas ordinary seaman on a liner\nbound for South America. The\ncruise gave him material for\nseveral stories which brought him\nto the attention of The Spur, and,\nwhen he later decided to go\nabroad, he was given the foreign\nassignment.\nPicketing Ruled\nLegal in Illinois\nCHICAGO. Jan. 1 (C.TF.S.).\nFor the first time in Illinois, a\ncourt of appellate jurisdiction to\nday held that a labor union may\npicket a company which does not\nemploy union members, and by\nplacards publicize the union views\nin a labor dispute. The ruling was\ngiven by the Cook county branch\nRailway Agent\nNever Sees Train\nKELSO, Wash., Jan. 1 (1.N.5.).\nH. D. Patterson is a railway agent\nwho never sees a train. He is\nstationed at Battle Ground, where\nno passenger trains call during\nI the week. The only train calling\nthere makes the run on Sunday\nwhen Patterson is off duty.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES, SATURDAY, JANUARY 1,193 S\nLong War Foreseen\nBy Nippon Premier\nBy JAMES R. YOUNG\nTOKYO, Jan. 1 (1.N.5.). \u2014A warning that Japan must pre\npare for a long period of hostilities \u201cto free the Chinese people\nfrom the pressure they are now suffering\u201d was uttered today\nby Premier Prince Fumimaro Konoye in a long New Year\u2019s\nmessage to the Mikado\u2019s subjects.\n\u201cJapan must make prepara\ntions for a long term battle more\nthoroughly than ever,\u201d he de\nclared.\n\u201cNo matter how troublesome\nit is, Japan must go its length\nin destroying the very source of\nso-called long term resistance\nagainst Japan and to free the\nChinese people from the pres\nsure they are now suffering.\nWANTS ONLY PEACE\n\"If Japan is asked what she\nwants, she will answer that she\nwants peace in the Orient and\npeace in the world, only she must\nclaim that other countries\nshould recognize the fact that in\norder to make the foundations\nof their peace firm and sound,\nmilitary action has been un\navoidable.\n\u201cJapan must expect many\nmore stages before winning the\nglory of ultimate victory. Japan\nmay only march ahead. Japan\nhas grown so big that nothing\nshort of this can serve the pur-\nChiang Rejects Peace Terms,\nQuits as Premier to Lead War\n(Continued from Page 1)\nbreak of guerrilla warfare against\nthe city\u2019s Japanese overlords\nushered in the new year in Shang\nhai today.\nIn the series of incidents, which\nelectrified the city and caused a\nnear panic in some sections, four\nJapanese soldiers were injured,\none seriously, and five Chinese\ncivilians were wounded. One of\nthe Chinese victims was a woman.\nGRENADES HIT SOLDIERS\nThe violence, which brought the\nwar back to Shanghai with a\nvengeance and led to grave fears\nof speedy Nipponese reprisals, be\ngan when hand grenades w\u00abe\ntossed at a group of 70 Japanese\nsoldiers walking in the Interna\ntional Settlement, south of Soo\nchow Creek, on a sight-seeing tour.\nIt was feared that the fact the\nbombings occurred in the foreign\narea would cause the Japanese\nauthorities here to take still more\nmeasures to bring the Interna\ntional Settlement under Nippon\u2019s\nrule.\nSEARCH STARTED\nPolice immediately threw a cor\ndon about the area where the\nbombs exploded and started a\nhouse to house search for the of\nfenders, believed to be members\nof the famous \"dare-to-die\u201d Chi\nnese band that has furtively re\nturned to Shanghai to harass the\nJapanese.\nAuthorities said the first gren\nades were thrown from a Chinese\nbuilding on Hankow road in the\nsettlement.\nOther bombs were thrown and\npistol shots were fired at two\nJapanese cotton mills on Robin\nson Road nearby.\nThe city first realized that new\nviolence had occurred when two\nshattering explosions were heard\non Hankow Road, near Rokien\nRoad. The Chinese woman was\nhit by the first grenades.\nInternational Newi Photo\natop their decks. This is the Army trans\nport Grant, now in Chinese waters, dis\nplaying a big emblem amidships. Can\u2019t\nmiss it, can yous\nI\npose of securing the safety of\nthe country.\u201d\nPANAY AFFAIR \u201cMISHAP\u201d\nKonoye referred to the attack\non the American gunboat Pansy\nin China by Japanese planes, the\nincident involving the British gun\nboat Ladybird, and other attacks\nas \"mishaps which shocked the\nwhole Japanese people, who keenly\nfelt responsibility for the unfortu\nnate mistakes.\u201d\nHe branded the Chinese govern\nment headed by Generalissimo\nChiang Kai-Shek a \"degraded and\nmerely destructive regime under\nthe influence of Communists.\u201d\nThe Premier also attacked for\neign powers which, he said, had\ndisplayed \"dogmatic prejudice\nagainst Japan,\u201d and added:\n\u201cIf European powers applied\nto the Far East even one-tenth\nof the flexible attitude manifest\nin their own continental prob\nlems, attainment of stability in\nthe Far East would be very sim\nple\nImmediately afterward, three\nmore bombs burst.\nANNIVERSARY DAY\nThe bombings climaxed an out\nburst of anti-Japanese feeling in\nShanghai which marked the\ntwenty-sixth anniversary of the\nfounding of the Chinese republic\nin 1912 by the late Sun Yat-Sen,\nfounder, first president and now\nvirtually a \u201cpatron saint\u201d of the\n\u201cnew China\u201d which is battling\nfor existence against Japan.\nBefore the bombing spread\ngrave apprehension through the\ncity, residents awoke to find the\ntown decorated with Chinese\nflags, in defiance of the Japanese\naiyl flooded with patriotic\npamphlets\u2014many of 'jwhich* were\naddressed to the press of the\nworld.\nLater, when the grenades were\ntossed at the Japanese troops,\n\u201cantitraitor\u201d pamphlets were\nhurled with them, first at the\ncorner of Fokien and Hankow\nRoads and a moment later at the\ncorner of Huphei and Hankow\nRoads.\nJAPANESE UNARMED\nThe Japanese at whom the\ngrenades were aimed were un\narmed, except that the soldiers\ncarried bayonets and their officers\ncarried pistols.\nSome accounts said the five Chi\nnese victims were wounded not\nby bomb fragments but by shots\nfired by the Japanese, but these\nassertions were not fully proved.\nOne grenade was tossed and\nshots were fired near the Japan-\nChina Spinning and Weaving\nCompany plant on Robinson Road\nin the western part of the settle\nment and another bomb was\nhurled at the Japanese Kung Dah\nNo. 3 Mill on Singapore Road. No\none was injured.\nIN AMERICAN SECTOR\nThe final incident, early in the\nafternoon, occurred at Gordon\nRoad, in the heart of the Ameri\ncan Marine sector. The American\nMarine headquarters is situated on\nGordon Road. This last bomb,\nthrown at the Japanese Naigai\nWata Kaisha Mill office, damaged\nthe wall but caused no casualties.\nBoston American\nRaises Its Price\nBOSTON, Jan. 1 (I.N.S.).\u2014Be\nginning next Monday, the price of\nthe Boston Evening American will\nbe 3 cents a copy, the newspaper\nannounced today. Reasons given\nwere increased costs.\nTORONTO, Ontario, Jan. 1\n(1.N.5.). Three Toronto daily\nnewspapers will raise the price of\ntheir publications to 3 cents, a\n1-cent increase, on Monday, it was\nannounced today.\nOHIO GETS WPA FUNDS\n(1.N.5.) Senator Robert J. Bui\nkey (D. of Ohio, today announced\npresidential approval of allot\nments for the following WPA\nprojects in his State: Geneva\u2014\ns4o,B\u00df3 for improvement of city\nstreets; Lorain county, $64,867 for\nimprovement of roads; Summit\ncounty, $194,781 for street im\nprovement, and village of Denni\nson. $31,759 for street improve\nment.\nMONOPOLY WAR\nIS POWER TEST\nFOR PRESIDENT\nParty Lines Are Cracked\nOn Business Situation\nBy \\RTHUR HACHTEN\n(1.N.5.) A snarling, strife-ridden\nCongress was assembling here to\nday for the regular session be\nginning Monday. Pre session state\nments pointed to a titantic strug\ngle over the Administration's \"war\nto a finish\u2019 with big business.\nWith party lines cracked wide\nopen on the business situation,\nPresident Roosevelt was believed\nto be facing a momentous test of\nhis leadership. His message on\nthe state of the nation, to be de\nlivered in person to a joint session\nof the Senate and House at 1:30\np. m., Eastern Standard Time,\nMonday, was eagerly awaited.\nSHARP DIVISION\nIn it he was expected to discuss\nforeign relations, national defense\nand the domestic trend in employ\nment. But on virtually every ma\njor piece of legislation before Con\ngress there was sharp division. De\nflections from the topheavy Demo\ncratic ranks plagued Administra\ntion leaders.\nNew Dealers, stymied during the\nlast and special session of Con\ngress by the President\u2019s apparent\n\"hands-off\u201d policy as regards Con\ngress, served notice they would\nnow take the offensive behind the\nbarrage against monopolies laid\ndown by Secretary of the Interior\nIckes and Assistant Attorney Gen\neral Jackson.\nFarm relief, housing, antilynch\ning, Government reorganization,\nregional resources planning, wage\nhours, tax revision, relief for the\nmillions of unemployed\u2014these al\nready were on the agenda for the\nimpending session.\nTENTATIVE PROGRAM\nBut all of them were crowded\nout of the limelight by the sudden\nwarfare over anti-monopoly legis\nlation and intimation by the Presi\ndent he would ask for more war\nships so the nation may be pre\npared for any contingency in the\ntroubled international scene.\nThe tentative program in the\nHouse, after the President\u2019s mes\nsage is heard and his budget for\nthe next fiscal year received, was\nto pass quickly several departmen\ntal appropriation bills and take ip\nthe tax revision measure the lat\nter part of this month.\nChicken Larceny\nPrice Rising, Too\nSALEM, N. J\u201e Jan. 1 (1.N.5.).\nJudge S. Rusling Leap announced\ntoday a New Year resolution,\ncharging chicken thieves $33 for\neach illicit chicken dinner.\nEstimating it cost $33 to take\nthe average criminal case through\nthe courts. Judge Leap said he\nwould consider each chicken a sep\narate case. The new price for pil\nfered poultry was announced\nafter John G. Glenn was fined\n$l9B, at $33 a chicken, and six\nmonths in jail for stealing six\nbirds.\nWind Blows Lake\nInto Town\u2019s Lap\nGRAND MARAIS, Minn., Jan.\n1 (I.N.S.).\u2014Stores were flooded\nand householders routed here to\nday as the wild waters of Lake\nSuperior moved in on this town.\nA stiff wind was blamed for the\nflood, which was accompanied by\nrapidly dropping temperatures.\nThe Seasons\nGreetings\nto our many friends\nand patrons in Wash\nington who have\nenabled us to have\nthe most successful\nyear in the history of\nour business.\nSMITH'S\nSTORAGE\n1313 You St. N. W.\nNO. 3343\n7*<Z\u00abpAdn\u00ab RE publie 1234\nJobless Insurance\nEffective Today in\n21 States and D. Q\n11,000,000 Workers Expected to Be Affected;\n$400,000,000 Fund Accumulated\nBy FREDERICK N. POLANGIN\n(1.N.5.) Into a nation beset with business recession, the\nnew year today ushered a planned economy for the unemployed\nmasses.\nThe jobless insurance program\nwent into effect today in 21 States\nand the District of Columbia, its\npurpose to lighten economic dis\nl tress of the nation and the unem\nployed.\nGovernment officials do not ex\npect a reneral decrease in the\nstrain on the relief burden as a\nresult of unemployment compen\nsation this year but they do ex\npect th.'.t eventually it will become\na medium for eliminating oe re\nducing the hazards that make for\neconomic instability.\n$400,000,000 READY\nMore than $400,000,000 has been\naccumulated through the imposi\ntion of a tax on employers\u2019 pay\nrolls for distribution in the follow\ning States in which the program\nwas inaugurated today:\nAlabama, Arizona, California,\nConnecticut, District of Columbia,\nLouisiana, Maine, Maryland, Mass\nachusetts, Minnesota, New Hamp\nshire, New York, North Carolina,\nOregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode\nIsland, Tennessee, Texas, Utah,\nVermont, Virginia and West Vir\nginia.\nIn all, upward of 11,000,000\nworkers are expected to be covered\nby the jobless insurance program\nin the 21 States and District of\nColumbia. Maritime, agricultural,\nand domestic workers are exempt.\nThe remaining States and Ter\nritories will come under the pro\ngram during 1939.\nGovernment officials have been\nhesitant to predict the full import\nof the program, admitting it will\nbe in the experimental stage for\nmany months. It was pointed out,\nhowever, that the current business\nrecession may prove a premature,\nyet nevertheless welcome, yard\nstick.\nTHOSE AFFECTED\nJobless insurance is for those\nwho lose their Jobs through no\nfault of their own. Immediately\nupon losing a job, the employe\nmust register at the employment\nservice headquarters in his dis\ntrict. He applies for benefits and\nenrolls for a new job at the same\ntime, the fundamental theory be\nhind the program being that it\nwill bridge the gap between the\ntime the worker loses his job and\nthe time he obtains another.\nFollowing a waiting period,\nusually about two weeks in most\nStates during which time a\nthorough investigation is made,\nthe jobless worker begins receiv\ning benefits if he is found to be\nqualified Payments run up to 16\nweeks in most States, with a maxi\nmum of sls a week and in many\ncases approximately 50 per cent\nof the salary.\nBenefits are computed either on\nthe basis of the length of employ\nment or on the total amount of\nwages for specified periods prior\nto the time the job was lost.\nW\n'.k cna/le /tape in t/ce A\n&a/eifl/b. m\n&or yxner and\nIK tee are etee/idy y.\n&t'er ey eftri f\nB 4ieU as a d&st in ettr ccninuinitif, wr\nn t>ttr ccnlinaed Mnrerdy es h\njut rit es*.\nt/ie\nanti j/la/t/iiness\nBritain, U. S. To\nJoin Navy Race\nLONDON, Jan. 1 (1.N.5.).\nPossibility that the United\nStates and Britain may in\nvoke the \u201cescalator clause\u201d in\nthe 1936 London naval treaty,\nif reports that Japan is build\ning or planning three 46,000-\nton battleships are confirmed,\nwas predicted in informed\ncircles today.\nThe London Daily Tele\ngraph said inclusion of three\nto five battlesh\u2019ps in the 1938-\n39 British naval program is\nregarded as a virtual cer\ntainty, to counteract German,\nItalian and Japanese naval\nconstruction.\nLUDLOW BLAST\nBY PRESIDENT\nEXPECTED SOON\nBy EARL GODWIN\nThe Administration takes the\nLudlow war referendum so seri\nously that it is expected President\nRoosevelt himself will lambast the\nHoosier Congressman\u2019s resolution\n\u2014almost ready for a vote and\nthat Secretary of War Woodring\nwill deliver two strong anti-Lud\nlow speeches.\nGovernment officials believe the\nLudlow resolution seriously weak\nens the country's prestige abroad\nin the more warlike and \"aggres\nsor\u2019' nations and that it would tie\nthe Government\u2019s nands in case\nit should be decided that a quick\nattack should be made on some\nnation which was about to iiwade\nAmerica\u2019s shore or interfere with\nAmerican rights abroad.\nThere is much strength for\nthe Ludlow plan of a popular\nreferendum before war can be de\nclared, that the Administration\nwants to give it as much adverse\npublicity as possible just before\nthe resolution comes up for a vote\nin the House next week.\nMrs. Rappaport\nWins Yule Prize\nGrand prize in a Christmas con\ntest sponsored by the Forest Hill\nCitizens\u2019 Association has been won\nby Mrs. S. S. Rappaport of 4614\nThirtieth St. N. W., it was an\nnounced today The prize has not\nyet been disclosed.\nThe association meets tomorrow\nat 8 p. m. in the Ben W. Morch\nbuilding. The annual dinner of the\ngroup will be held January 25 at\nthe Columbia Country Club.","height":"25742","width":"20137"}}
